le's sexuality, violence against disabled women, or rethinking the use of disabled people as a metaphor for life under Japanese colonial rule or under the U.S. military occupation, Kim shows how the possibility of life with disability that is free from violence depends on the creation of a space and time where cure is seen as a negotiation rather than a necessity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aPeople with disabilities in mass media. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxCarezKorea (South). 0aPeople with disabilitiesxRehabilitationzKorea (South). 0aSociology of disabilityzKorea (South). 4aAAS Book Award Winners. 4aAsian Studies Association book awards. 4aJames B. Palais Book Prize winner. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / People with Disabilities.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2017z978311069634940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822373513zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822373513423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822373513.jpg  a978-3-11-069634-9  DUK eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles